It looks like you’re referring to **CAN A, CAN B, and CAN High** in the context of the **Controller Area Network (CAN bus)** used in vehicles and embedded systems. These terms are often mixed up, so I’ll break them down clearly and then compare them in detail.

---

## 🧠 CAN A vs CAN B vs CAN High (CAN_H) — Detailed Comparison

| Feature                       | CAN A                                                      | CAN B                                                | CAN High (CAN_H)                                     |
| ----------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
| **Full name / role**          | High-speed CAN network (Powertrain CAN in many vehicles)   | Low-speed or Body CAN network                        | One wire of the differential CAN pair                |
| **Purpose**                   | Critical systems communication (engine, ABS, transmission) | Comfort/body systems (windows, lights, infotainment) | Carries differential signal with CAN_L               |
| **Speed range**               | Typically 250 kbps to 1 Mbps                               | Typically 33 kbps to 125 kbps                        | Depends on CAN type (high-speed or low-speed CAN)    |
| **Network type**              | High-speed CAN bus segment                                 | Low-speed fault-tolerant CAN                         | Physical signal line (not a network itself)          |
| **Signal role**               | Logical CAN channel (network classification)               | Logical CAN channel (network classification)         | Physical voltage line (dominant/recessive signaling) |
| **Voltage behavior (idle)**   | ~2.5V baseline (varies by system)                          | ~5V in fault-tolerant systems                        | ~2.5V idle (recessive state reference)               |
| **Voltage (dominant state)**  | ~3.5V (varies slightly by ECU)                             | Varies depending on implementation                   | ~3.5V when dominant                                  |
| **Voltage (recessive state)** | ~2.5V                                                      | ~5V or split biasing (low-speed CAN)                 | ~2.5V                                                |
| **Paired with**               | CAN_L (High-speed differential pair)                       | CAN_L (or second line in fault-tolerant pair)        | Always paired with CAN_L                             |
| **Topology role**             | Backbone for real-time control systems                     | Secondary comfort network                            | Physical layer component                             |
| **Fault tolerance**           | Medium (requires termination resistors)                    | High (can operate in degraded mode)                  | Depends on full differential pair health             |
| **Termination**               | 120Ω at both ends of bus                                   | May not require strict termination                   | Works with CAN_L termination system                  |
| **Examples in cars**          | Engine ECU, gearbox ECU, ABS                               | Door modules, AC, infotainment                       | Exists in every CAN high-speed network               |

---

## 🔧 Key Concept: The BIG confusion

Many people mix these up, but they are actually **different abstraction levels**:

### 1. CAN A and CAN B = NETWORKS (logical buses)

These are **separate CAN networks inside a vehicle**:

* **CAN A** → critical/high-speed systems
* **CAN B** → body/comfort/low-speed systems

👉 Think of them as **two separate highways**

---

### 2. CAN High (CAN_H) = PHYSICAL SIGNAL LINE

CAN does NOT work on a single wire.

It uses **differential signaling**:

* **CAN_H (CAN High)**
* **CAN_L (CAN Low)**

👉 Think of them as a **twisted pair of wires carrying opposite signals**

---

## ⚡ How CAN High actually works (important)

| State            | CAN_H Voltage | CAN_L Voltage | Meaning                  |
| ---------------- | ------------- | ------------- | ------------------------ |
| Recessive (idle) | ~2.5V         | ~2.5V         | No dominant data         |
| Dominant (0 bit) | ~3.5V         | ~1.5V         | Data transmission active |

👉 The receiver reads the **difference between CAN_H and CAN_L**, not absolute voltage.

---

## 🧩 Simple mental model

| Term     | Think of it as                            |
| -------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| CAN A    | Fast highway for engine + safety systems  |
| CAN B    | Slower street for comfort features        |
| CAN High | One wire of a 2-wire communication system |

---

## ⚠️ Common misunderstanding

* ❌ CAN High is NOT a separate network like CAN A or CAN B
* ❌ CAN A/B are NOT physical wires
* ✅ CAN High is part of every CAN network physically
* ✅ CAN A/B are logical divisions of CAN networks in vehicles

